fully considering the materials and process of making, and connecting process to product and people, he demonstrates how objects act on those who look at, use, and acquire them. He reveals how objects retain aspects of their local fabrication while absorbing additional meanings in subtle and unexpected ways as they move through space and time. In emphasizing multiple centers of art production amid constantly changing contexts, Cooke moves beyond regional histories driven by geography, nation-state, time period, or medium.Beautifully illustrated, Global Objects traces the social lives of objects from creation to purchase, and from use to experienced meaning, charting exciting new directions in art history.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 06. Mrz 2024) 0aArt and society. 0aArt objects. 7aART / History / General.2bisacsh  aAccuracy and precision.  aApproximation.  aArtisan.  aBeautifully illustrated.  aBootstrapping (statistics).  aCassini's laws.  aChinese ceramics.  aCoefficient.  aCommodity.  aConfidence interval.  aConnected Art History.  aDesign.  aDyeing.  aEarthenware.  aEccentricity vector.  aEdward S. Cooke, Jr.  aEmbroidery.  aEmpirical distribution function.  aEstimation.  aEstimator.  aExcitation (magnetic).  aFritware.  aFurniture.  aGiambologna.  aGlazing (window).  aGold leaf.  aGourd.  aGujarat.  aHegemony.  aIkat.  aIllustration.  aInvestor.  aJingdezhen.  aJoint probability distribution.  aLaboratory.  aLacquer.  aLoom.  aMarquetry.  aMetalworking.  aMiddle Ages.  aNatural satellite.  aOrbital resonance.  aOttoman Empire.  aParameter.  aPorcelain.  aPottery.  aProbability.  aRandom variable.  aRegional assembly (England).  aReincarnation.  aSculpture.  aScuola Normale Superiore di Pisa.  aSemi-major and semi-min